{{dablink|This article is about a historic site in Illinois named '''Lewis and Clark'''.  For other uses, see [[Lewis and Clark (disambiguation)]].}}

[[File:Camp Dubois reconstruction 034.jpg|thumb|A reconstruction of [[Camp Dubois]] is on the grounds of the historic site.]]
The '''Lewis and Clark State Historic Site''' opened in 2002 and is owned and operated by the Illinois Department of Natural Resources Division of Historic Preservation (formerly [[Illinois Historic Preservation Division]]).  The site, located in [[Hartford, Illinois]], commemorates [[Camp Dubois|Camp River Dubois]], the camp of the [[Lewis and Clark Expedition]] from December 1803 to May 1804.  The site is National Trail Site #1 on the [[Lewis and Clark National Historic Trail]] and is located directly off the Confluence Bike Trail, part of the [[Confluence Greenway]].  The site is at the southern end of the [[Meeting of the Great Rivers Scenic Route]].

The Lewis and Clark State Historic Site is situated on the dry side of the Chain of Rocks Levee, approximately 1/4 mile from the [[Illinois]] shore of the [[Mississippi River]].  The site replaced Lewis and Clark State Park, which is no longer in existence.{{cn|date=July 2013}}

Main attractions at the site include a {{convert|14000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} interpretive center and an outdoor replica of [[Camp Dubois|Camp River Dubois]].  The interpretive center contains a theater, multiple hands-on exhibits and displays, and a {{convert|55|ft|m|adj=on}} full-scale cutaway keelboat.

