{{nihongo|'''Sumihiko Hatsushima'''|初島 住彦|Hatsushima Sumihiko|extra=September 1906 – January 22, 2008}} was a [[Japanese people|Japanese]] [[botanist]]. In scholarly works using the [[Latin alphabet]], his name is generally [[Romanization|romanised]] as "'''Sumihiko Hatusima'''" following the [[Kunrei-shiki|"Kunrei" system]].<ref name="IPNI_AuthorDetails_Hatusima">{{cite web|url=http://www.ipni.org/ipni/idAuthorSearch.do?id=20057-1&back_page=%2Fipni%2FeditAdvAuthorSearch.do%3Ffind_abbreviation%3D%26find_surname%3Dhatusima%26find_isoCountry%3D%26find_forename%3D%26output_format%3Dnormal|title=Author Details Hatusima, Sumihiko (1906-2008) |publisher=www.ipni.org [[IPNI]]|accessdate=2009-09-19}}</ref><ref name="NationaalHerbariumNederland_Collectors_HatusimaSumihiko">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaalherbarium.nl/FMCollectors/H/HatusimaS.htm|title=Hatusima, Sumihiko|date=24 July 2007|publisher=[[National Herbarium of the Netherlands]]|accessdate=2009-09-17}}</ref>

Hatsushima was born in [[Nagasaki Prefecture]], [[Japan]] in 1906.<ref name="IPNI_AuthorDetails_Hatusima"/><ref name=NationaalHerbariumNederland_Collectors_HatusimaSumihiko/>
His tertiary studies and early lectureship was at [[Kyushu Imperial University]], where he was awarded a [[PhD|doctorate]] in 1942.<ref name=NationaalHerbariumNederland_Collectors_HatusimaSumihiko/>
He accompanied [[Ryōzō Kanehira]] on a collecting expedition in [[New Guinea]] in 1940.<ref name=NationaalHerbariumNederland_Collectors_HatusimaSumihiko/>  Hatsushima returned to Austronesia in a collecting expedition to [[The Philippines]] in 1964.<ref name=NationaalHerbariumNederland_Collectors_HatusimaSumihiko/>

Hatsushima died in 2008.<ref name="Tsumura_TheJournalofJapaneseBotany_2008Apr20_Hosoyamada_HatsushimaObituary">{{cite web|url=http://www.tsumura.co.jp/English/kampo/plant/083/author.html|title=The Journal of Japanese Botany|last=HOSOYAMADA|first=Saburo|date=April 20, 2008|publisher=Tsumura and co|accessdate=2009-09-17}}</ref>

