[[File:Pterygotus anglicus Haeckel.jpg|thumb|Life restoration of ''[[Pterygotus]]'', one of the first eurypterids described (in 1839).]]
This '''timeline of eurypterid research''' is a chronologically ordered list of important [[fossil]] discoveries, controversies of interpretation, and [[Biological taxonomy|taxonomic]] revisions of [[Eurypterid|eurypterids]], a group of extinct aquatic [[Arthropod|arthropods]] closely related to modern [[Horseshoe crab|horseshoe crabs]] that lived during the [[Paleozoic]] [[Era (geology)|Era]].

The scientific study of eurypterids began in the early 19th century when [[James Ellsworth De Kay|James E. DeKay]] recognized a fossil that had previously been described as that of a fish as arthropod in nature. Though DeKay erronously believed the fossil to represent a [[crustacean]] and a missing link between [[Trilobite|trilobites]] and [[Branchiopoda|branchiopods]], the fossil became the type species of first ever eurypterid to be scientifically described, ''[[Eurypterus remipes]]'', in [[1825 in paleontology|1825]].<ref name=":2">Clarke, J. K., Ruedemann R. (1912) "[[wikisource:The_Eurypterida_of_New_York/Volume_1/Eurypteridae|The Eurypterida of New York]]"</ref>

As of 2018, over 250 species of eurypterids have been described.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dunlop|first=J. A.|last2=Penney|first2=D.|last3=Jekel|first3=D.|date=2015|title=A summary list of fossil spiders and their relatives (version 16.0)|url=http://www.wsc.nmbe.ch/resources/fossils/Fossils16.0.pdf|journal=World Spider Catalog|publisher=Natural History Museum Bern|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> The most recent species to be described is ''[[Soligorskopterus|Soligorskopterus tchepeliensis]]''.<ref name="belarus">{{cite journal|last1=Plax|first1=Dmitry P.|last2=Lamsdell|first2=James C.|last3=Vrazo|first3=Matthew B.|last4=Barbikov|first4=Dmitry V.|year=2018|title=A new genus of eurypterid (Chelicerata, Eurypterida) from the Upper Devonian salt deposits of Belarus|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326233486|journal=[[Journal of Paleontology]]|doi=10.1017/jpa.2018.11}}</ref>

==19th century==
[[File:The_Eurypterida_of_New_York_figure_1.jpg|link=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:The_Eurypterida_of_New_York_figure_1.jpg|thumb|Figure of ''[[Eurypterus remipes]]'' by [[James Ellsworth De Kay|James E. De Kay]] (1825).]]

=== 1810s ===
'''[[1818 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1818</span>]]'''{{anchor|1818}}

* The first eurypterid fossil to be discovered is unearthed in rocks in [[New York (state)|New York]] of [[Silurian]] age. It is described by Dr. S. L. Mitchill as an example of the fish ''[[Silurus]]'', possibly due to the [[catfish]]-like appearance of its carapace.<ref name=":2" />

=== 1820s ===
'''[[1825 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1825</span>]]'''{{anchor|1825}}

* [[James Ellsworth De Kay|James E. DeKay]] recognized the fossil described by Mitchill as an [[arthropod]] and named it ''[[Eurypterus remipes]]'', the first eurypterid to be described scientifically. DeKay interpreted the animal as a [[crustacean]] and as the missing link between [[Trilobite|trilobites]] and [[Branchiopoda|branchiopods]].<ref name=":2" />

=== 1830s ===
'''[[1839 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1839</span>]]'''{{anchor|1839}}

* [[Louis Agassiz]] described the new genus ''Pterygotus'', believing the fossils to represent a large fish. The type species is named ''P. problematicus''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.se/books?id=hOxCAQAAMAAJ&dq=pterygotus+winged+one+name&hl=sv&source=gbs_navlinks_s|title=The Silurian System, Founded on Geological Researches in the Counties of Salop, Hereford, Radnor, Montgomery, Caermarthen, Brecon, Pembroke, Monmouth, Gloucester, Worcester, and Stafford: With Descriptions of the Coalfields and Overlying Formations|last=Murchison|first=Roderick Impey|publisher=Albemarle Street|year=1839|isbn=|location=|pages=606}}</ref>

=== 1840s ===
'''[[1844 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1844</span>]]'''{{anchor|1844}}

* Agassiz recognized ''Pterygotus'' as an arthropod after the discovery of more complete remains, he classified it as a [[crustacean]] of the [[Entomostraca]] subclass.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=M'Coy|first=Frederick|date=|year=2009|title=XLI.—On the classification of some British fossil Crustacea, with notices of new forms in the University Collection at Cambridge|journal=Annals and Magazine of Natural History|volume=4 (24)|issue=24|pages=392–414|doi=10.1080/03745486009494858}}</ref>

=== 1850s ===
'''[[1856 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1856</span>]]'''{{anchor|1856}}
*[[John William Salter]] described the new genus ''[[Himantopterus]]'' and the new species ''H. acumintus'', ''H. banksii'', ''H. bilobus'', ''H. lanceolatus'', ''H. maximus'' and ''H. perorntus''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C51ZAAAAYAAJ|title=On some new Crustacea from the uppermost Silurian Rocks|work=[[Quarterly Journal of the Geological Society of London]]|last=Salter|first= John W.|year=1856|volume=12|pp=26–34}}</ref>

=== 1880s ===
'''[[1889 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1889</span>]]'''{{anchor|1889}}
*Matthew described the new genus and species ''[[Bunodella|Bunodella horrida]]'' as a crustacean.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/10787421|title=On some remarkable organisms of the Silurian and Devonian rocks in southern New Brunswick|first=G. F.|last=Matthew|year=1889|journal=Transactions of the Royal Society of Canada|volume=6|issue=4|pp=49–62}}</ref>

==20th century==
===1900s===
'''[[1901 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1901</span>]]'''{{anchor|1901}}
*[[Charles Emerson Beecher]] described the new genus and species ''[[Strabops|Strabops thacheri]]'' as the only Cambrian eurypterid.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.ajsonline.org/content/s4-12/71/364.extract|title=Discovery of Eurypterid remains in the Cambrian of Missouri|last=Beecher|first=C. E.|year=1901|journal=[[American Journal of Science]]|volume=12|pp=364–366|doi=10.2475/ajs.s4-12.71.364}}</ref>
'''[[1903 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1903</span>]]'''{{anchor|1903}}
*Clifton J. Sarle described the new species ''Pterygotus monroensis'' and ''Eurypterus pittsfordensis''. The new genus and species ''[[Hughmilleria|Hughmilleria socialis]]'' with the variety ''H. socialis'' var. ''robusta'' is also described.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/43853136|title=A new eurypterid fauna from the base of the Salina of western New York|first=Clifton J.|last=Sarle|publisher=New York State Museum Bulletin|volume=69|pp=1080–1108}}</ref>
'''[[1907 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1907</span>]]'''{{anchor|1907}}
*[[John Mason Clarke]] described the new species ''Pterygotus otisius'', ''Hughmilleria shawangunk'', ''Eurypterus maria'', ''E. myops'', ''E. cicerops'' and ''E. cestrotus''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/34888389|title=The ''Eurypterus'' shales of the Shawangunk Mountains in eastern New York|work=New York State Museum Bulletin|year=1907|last=Clarke|first=John M.|volume=107|pp=295–310}}</ref>

===1930s===
'''[[1939 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1939</span>]]'''{{anchor|1939}}
*Gilbert Oscar Raasch referred ''Strabops'' to the order [[Aglaspida]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wwa0sxlPI-0C|title=Cambrian Merostomata|first=Gilbert Oscar|last=Raasch|journal=[[Geological Society of America]]|volume=19|pp=1–146|isbn=9780813720197|doi=10.1130/SPE19}}</ref>

===1950s===
'''[[1950 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1950</span>]]'''{{anchor|1950}}
*Kjellesvig-Waering described the new species ''Hughmilleria bellistriata''.<ref>{{cite journal|jstor=1299503|title=A New Silurian Hughmilleria from West Virginia|last=Kjellesvig-Waering|first=Erik N.|journal=Journal of Paleontology|volume=24|issue=2|pp=226–228}}</ref>
'''[[1951 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1951</span>]]'''{{anchor|1951}}
*Kjellesvig-Waering described the new family [[Hughmilleriidae]], composed of ''Hughmilleria'', ''Slimonia'', ''Grossopterus'', ''Lepidoderma'', ''Hastimima'' and the new genus ''[[Salteropterus|Salteropterus abbreviatus]]'' (formerly a species of ''Eurypterus''), leaving the Pterygotidae monotypic.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kjellesvig-Waering|first=Erik N.|date=1951|title=Downtonian (Silurian) Eurypterida from Perton, near Stoke Edith, Herefordshire|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/geological-magazine/article/downtonian-silurian-eurypterida-from-perton-near-stoke-edith-herefordshire/8AB13FF21997A48304D5DF9090AD3585|journal=Geological Magazine|language=en|volume=88|issue=1|pages=1–24|doi=10.1017/S0016756800068874|issn=1469-5081|via=}}</ref>
'''[[1957 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1957</span>]]'''{{anchor|1957}}
*Pirozhnikov described two new species, ''Rhenopterus matarakensis'' and ''R. schiraensis''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Remains of Gigantostraca from the series of Matakara (Devonian of the North Minusinsk Depression)|journal=Vsesojuzuoe Paleontologiceskoe Obchestvo Ezegodnik|year=1957|last=Pirozhnikov|first=L. P.|volume=16|pp=207–213|issn=0201-9280|oclc=229469975}}</ref>

===1960s===
'''[[1961 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1961</span>]]'''{{anchor|1961}}
*Kjellesvig-Waering described the new species ''Salteropterus longilabium'', ''Pterygotus'' (''Pterygotus'') ''denticulatus'', ''P.'' (''P.'') ''grandidentatus'', ''P.'' (''P.'') ''lightbodyi'', ''Carcinosoma harleyi'' and ''Dolichopterus bulbosus''. The new genus ''[[Parahughmilleria]]'' is described with ''P. salteri'' as the type species. ''Hughmilleria bellistriata'', ''H. phelpsae'' and ''Eurypterus maria'' are moved to this genus. The subgenus ''Erettopterus'' is regarded as a new genus and is separated into two new subgenera, ''E.'' (''Erettopterus''), including the new species ''E.'' (''E.'') ''brodiei'', ''E.'' (''E.'') ''marstoni'' and ''E.'' (''E.'') ''spatulatus'', and ''E.'' (''Truncatiramus''), including the new subspecies ''E.'' (''T.'') ''gigas megalodon''. The genus ''Hughmilleria'' is splitted into two new subgenera, ''H.'' (''Hughmilleria'') and ''H.'' (''[[Nanahughmilleria]]'').<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kjellesvig-Waering|first=Erik N.|date=1961|title=The Silurian Eurypterida of the Welsh Borderland|journal=Journal of Paleontology|volume=35|issue=4|pages=789–835|jstor=1301214}}</ref>
'''[[1966 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1966</span>]]'''{{anchor|1966}}
*Kjellesvig-Waering and Willard P. Leutze described the new species ''[[Bassipterus|Bassipterus virginicus]]'' (a new genus), ''Drepanopterus nodosus'' and ''Erettopterus'' (''Truncatiramus'') ''exophthalmus''. The species ''H.'' (''N.'') ''phelpsae'' is classified as a new genus, ''[[Pittsfordipterus]]''. ''Rhenopterus matarakensis'' is assigned to ''Parahughmilleria'', ''R. schiraensis'' is assigned to ''Hughmilleria'' (''Nanahughmilleria'').<ref>{{cite journal|jstor=1299503|title=A New Silurian Hughmilleria from West Virginia|last=Kjellesvig-Waering|first=Erik N.|journal=Journal of Paleontology|volume=24|issue=2|pp=226–228}}</ref>

===1980s===
'''[[1980 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">1980</span>]]'''{{anchor|1980}}
*Mario Hünicken described the new genus and species ''[[Megarachne|Megarachne servinei]]'' as a [[mygalomorph]] spider.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A giant fossil spider (''Megarachne servinei'') from Bajo de Véliz, Upper Carboniferous, Argentina|last=Hünicken|first=Mario A.|year=1980|journal=Boletin de la Academia Nacional de Ciencias, Córdoba, Argentina|volume=53|pages=317–341}}</ref>

==21st century==
===2000s===
'''[[2005 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">2005</span>]]'''{{anchor|2005}}
*Selden, Corronca and Hünicken recognized ''Megarachne servinei'' as a mycteroptid eurypterid.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Selden|first=Paul A|last2=Corronca|first2=José A|last3=Hünicken|first3=Mario A|date=2005-03-22|title=The true identity of the supposed giant fossil spider ''Megarachne''|url=|journal=Biology Letters|volume=1|issue=1|pages=44–48|doi=10.1098/rsbl.2004.0272|issn=1744-9561|pmc=1629066|pmid=17148124|via=}}</ref>
'''[[2006 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">2006</span>]]'''{{anchor|2006}}
*Tetlie interpreted ''Hughmilleria banksii'' as a new genus, ''[[Herefordopterus]]''. In addition, the species ''Hughmilleria acuminata'' was synonymized with ''Herefordopterus banksii''.
'''[[2007 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">2007</span>]]'''{{anchor|2007}}
*Tetlie, Selden & Ren described the new species ''Hughmilleria wangi''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/epdf/10.1111/j.1475-4983.2007.00651.x|title=A new Silurian eurypterid (Arthropoda: Chelicerata) from China.|authors=Erik Tetlie, Paul A Selden, Dong Ren|journal=Palaeontology|volume=50|issue=3|pp=619–625|doi=10.1111/j.1475-4983.2007.00651.x|date=2007}}</ref>
*Miller and Tetlie determine that ''Bunodella'' represents an indeterminate species of ''Acutiramus''. However, it is not formally synonymized and is regarded as a ''nomen dubium''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.bioone.org/doi/abs/10.1666/05127.1|title=The presumed Synziphosuran ''Bunodella horrida'' Matthew, 1889 (Silurian; Cunningham Creek Formation, New Brunswick, Canada) is a eurypterid|last1=Miller|first1=Randall F.|last2=Tetlie|first2=O. Erik|volume=81|issue=3|pp=588-590|doi=10.1666/05127.1|year=2007}}</ref>

===2010s===
'''[[2012 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">2012</span>]]'''{{anchor|2012}}
*Shpinev described the new species ''Parahughmilleria longa'' and ''Nanahughmilleria notosibirica''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://rd.springer.com/article/10.1134/S0031030112040119|title=On some eurypterids (Eurypterida, Chelicerata) from the Devonian of South Siberia|last=Shpinev|first=E. S.|year=2012|volume=46|issue=4|pp=370–377|doi=10.1134/S0031030112040119}}</ref>
'''[[2015 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">2015</span>]]'''{{anchor|2015}}
*Poschmann transferred ''Erieopterus statzi'' to the genus ''Parahughmilleria''. The new genus and species ''[[Wiedopterus|Wiedopterus noctua]]'' is described.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Poschmann|first=Markus|date=2015-12-01|title=Sea scorpions (Chelicerata, Eurypterida) from the Lower Devonian (Siegenian) of the Lahrbach Valley/Westerwald area (SW Germany, Rhineland-Palatinate)|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12542-015-0261-9|journal=Paläontologische Zeitschrift|language=en|volume=89|issue=4|pages=783–793|doi=10.1007/s12542-015-0261-9|issn=0031-0220}}</ref>
*Lamsdell ''et al.'' described the new genus and species ''[[Pentecopterus|Pentecopterus decorahensis]]'', the oldest eurypterid known to date.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lamsdell|first1=James C.|last2=Briggs|first2=Derek E. G.|last3=Liu|first3=Huaibao|last4=Witzke|first4=Brian J.|last5=McKay|first5=Robert M.|date=2015|title=The oldest described eurypterid: a giant Middle Ordovician (Darriwilian) megalograptid from the Winneshiek Lagerstätte of Iowa|url=http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2148/15/169|journal=[[BMC Evolutionary Biology]]|volume=15|pages=169|doi=10.1186/s12862-015-0443-9|pmc=4556007|pmid=26324341}}</ref>
'''[[2017 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">2017</span>]]'''{{anchor|2017}}
*Vrazo & Ciurca described the new ichnogenus and ichnospecies ''[[Arcuites|Arcuites bertiensis]]'', interpreted as traces of a swimming eurypterid.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/pala.12336/abstract|title=New trace fossil evidence for eurypterid swimming behaviour|last1=Vrazo|first1=Matthew B.|last2=Ciurca|first2=Samuel J.|journal=[[Palaeontology (journal)|Palaeontology]]|volume=61|issue=7|pp=1–18|year=2017|doi=10.1111/pala.12336|issn=1475-4983}}</ref>
'''[[2018 in paleontology|<span style="color:#14145C;">2018</span>]]'''{{anchor|2018}}
*Plax ''et al.'' described the new genus and species ''[[Soligorskopterus|Soligorskopterus tchepeliensis]]'', to date the most recently described eurypterid genus and species.<ref name="belarus" />

